{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500155","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500155"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:09:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:09:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1617"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1617"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.03,0.69,0.07,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1617"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91349"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1617"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1617"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75098"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1800"},{"type":"tags","id":"2149"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1555"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31246"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/91349"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old man undergoes a radical right nephrectomy for a Stage III renal cell carcinoma. The tumour is 8 cm diameter and in the upper pole of the kidney. He makes good progress post-operatively and by day three is back on a normal diet. On day five the following observation is made of his wound drain (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely to have been damaged?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Common bile duct","Stomach","Cisterna chyli","Ureter","Small bowel"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWith the radical surgery required for a locally advanced renal carcinoma, any of the adjacent structures listed could have been damaged during the procedure. The milky-white material in the drain bag is chyle. The leak must be from either the region of the \u003Cstrong\u003Ecisterna chyli\u003C/strong\u003E or the thoracic duct. The cisterna chyli is situated immediately behind the aorta at the L1, 2 level. This patient had recently undergone a radical nephrectomy and this leak only became evident once the patient started back on a normal diet. If the drain had still not been in position, the patient may have developed a chylous ascites.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETreatment of this unusual complication can be difficult. A conservative approach with a low fat diet might work - this should reduce the volume of chyle being produced. If this fails the patient might be put on total parenteral nutrition. Persistence of the leak may then required surgical intervention and clipping of the lymphatic vessels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the collection in the bag had been due to a bile duct injury, the liquid would be green and relatively clear. Injuries to the stomach or small bowel would be associated with pale or clear fluid. The ureter would have been ligated during the surgery and even if it was left open, no urine would drain out of it.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Inadvertent damage to adjacent structures is always a risk during major abdominal surgery."],"references":["Aerts J, Matas A, Sutherland D, Kandaswamy R. Chylous ascites requiring surgical intervention after donor nephrectomy: case series and single center experience. Am J Transplant. 2010;10(1):124-8. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3634560/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75098"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1617"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15176"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15176","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15176"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ed9079c2-0833-4ed6-bb1c-b586bfe028e3.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ed9079c2-0833-4ed6-bb1c-b586bfe028e3.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75098"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-15T17:45:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-15T17:45:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1617"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"91349"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedi